    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Social reach</strong> is the total number of unique users who see your content during a given period. Unlike impressions — which count every view including repeats — reach counts each person exactly once. A post with 5,000 reach was seen by 5,000 distinct people, even if some of them saw it three times.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Good benchmark</div>
            <div class="tms-value">20-30% of followers (Instagram)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Social Media</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Counts</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Unique users only</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Reach is the metric that tells you the real size of your social audience — not how many times your content played, but how many actual human beings encountered it. Get it right and your content strategy gets sharper. Ignore it and you'll optimise for inflated numbers that mean nothing.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is social reach?</h2>
        <p>Social reach quantifies how many distinct individuals viewed your social content within a reporting window — typically 7 or 28 days for page-level metrics, or the lifetime of the post for content-level metrics. Platforms deduplicates viewers, so someone who scrolled past your Instagram post on Monday and saw it again in a Story on Thursday still counts as 1 in your reach figure.</p>
        <p>This deduplication is what makes reach the preferred metric for audience measurement. It directly answers: "How many people did this content actually reach?"</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">How platforms count reach</div>
          <p>Facebook and Instagram count a view when content enters the viewport. LinkedIn counts unique accounts that loaded the post. TikTok reports unique viewers per video. These definitions are not identical, so cross-platform reach comparisons require context.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why does reach matter for social media strategy?</h2>
        <p>Reach is the denominator behind every other social metric that matters. Without knowing how many people actually saw your content, you cannot meaningfully interpret engagement rate, click-through rate, or conversion data. Five reasons reach belongs in every performance review:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>True audience measurement.</strong> Impressions inflate numbers because repeat views pile up. Reach cuts through the noise and shows you the real headcount.</li>
          <li><strong>Content quality signal.</strong> Falling reach on consistent posting frequency usually means the algorithm is down-distributing your content — a signal to test new formats or topics.</li>
          <li><strong>Campaign benchmarking.</strong> Comparing reach across post types (Reels vs. carousels vs. static) tells you which formats the algorithm rewards for your specific account.</li>
          <li><strong>Organic vs. paid distinction.</strong> Platforms report organic and paid reach separately. Tracking both shows whether your paid investment is expanding reach or just amplifying to the same audience twice.</li>
          <li><strong>Engagement rate denominator.</strong> Engagement rate = total engagements / reach. Using reach rather than follower count gives you a truer picture of how resonant your content actually is.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How social reach works</h2>
        <p>Every time you publish a post, the platform's algorithm decides how many people to show it to and in what order. Initial distribution goes to a fraction of your followers. If that sample engages at a higher rate than your account average, the algorithm expands distribution — increasing reach. If they don't, distribution tapers off.</p>
        <p>This is why the first 60 minutes after posting matters so much. Early engagement velocity is the strongest signal that triggers expanded reach.</p>

        <h3>Organic reach</h3>
        <p>Organic reach comes from the algorithm's unpaid distribution to your followers and, when content performs well, to non-followers through hashtags, explore pages, or algorithmic recommendations. Organic reach has declined consistently since 2014 as platforms push brands toward paid promotion.</p>

        <h3>Paid reach</h3>
        <p>Paid reach comes from ad spend targeting users beyond your existing followers. Platforms combine both into total reach on reporting dashboards, so always check the breakdown to understand what you're actually earning versus buying.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Types of reach — organic, paid, viral</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Type</th><th>Source</th><th>Cost</th><th>When to prioritise</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Organic reach</strong></td>
                <td>Algorithm + followers</td>
                <td>Free</td>
                <td>Building long-term audience trust</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Paid reach</strong></td><td>Ad targeting</td><td>CPM-based</td><td>Launching campaigns to new audiences</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Viral reach</strong></td><td>Shares + saves from current viewers</td><td>Free</td><td>Content that triggers strong emotional response</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Influencer reach</strong></td><td>Creator's audience overlap</td><td>Collaboration fee</td><td>Breaking into a new demographic or niche</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real reach examples</h2>
        <p>Abstract metrics become clearer with concrete numbers. Here's what reach looks like across different accounts and content types.</p>

        <h3>Example 1 — Real estate agent, Instagram</h3>
        <p>A real estate agent with 8,000 followers publishes a static listing photo that reaches 3,200 people — 40% of followers, typical for organic static content. The same agent publishes a Reel showing a home tour and reaches 8,500 people — 106% of followers, because Reels get distributed beyond the follower base. The Reel achieves 2.6x the reach for the same effort.</p>

        <h3>Example 2 — B2B brand, LinkedIn</h3>
        <p>A B2B SaaS company tracks reach by format over 90 days: carousels average 6,000 reach per post, text-only posts average 4,200, and videos average 3,800. The data makes the decision: prioritise carousels for top-of-funnel reach, use video for warm retargeting where engagement depth matters more than raw audience size.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Reach vs. impressions — which metric to use</h2>
        <p>Both metrics come from the same events but answer different questions. Choose the right one based on the goal.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use reach when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Measuring how many people know about your brand</li>
              <li>Setting audience-size benchmarks for campaigns</li>
              <li>Calculating true engagement rate</li>
              <li>Comparing content formats for distribution efficiency</li>
              <li>Reporting on awareness-stage campaign performance</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use impressions when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Analysing ad frequency and potential fatigue</li>
              <li>Buying media on CPM terms</li>
              <li>Understanding brand recall through repeated exposure</li>
              <li>Tracking feed visibility, not unique audience size</li>
              <li>Measuring share-of-voice against competitors</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for improving social reach</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Use platform-prioritised formats.</strong> On Instagram, Reels consistently outperform static images by 2-3x in reach. On LinkedIn, carousels and text posts with strong hooks beat native video. Each platform telegraphs which formats it's currently rewarding — match it.</li>
          <li><strong>Post when your audience is active.</strong> Check your platform's audience insights for peak active hours. Posting 30 minutes before peak gives the algorithm time to start distributing before engagement spikes.</li>
          <li><strong>Drive engagement in the first hour.</strong> Reply to every comment in the first 60 minutes. Ask a question in your caption. Reshare to Stories immediately. Early engagement velocity is the strongest algorithmic distribution trigger.</li>
          <li><strong>Separate organic and paid reach in reports.</strong> Never celebrate total reach without checking the split. Rising total reach driven entirely by paid spend with flat organic reach means your content isn't earning algorithmic distribution — it's being bought.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit your posting frequency.</strong> Posting too frequently with low-engagement content teaches the algorithm that your account produces average content. Reduce frequency, improve quality per post, and let reach recover.</li>
          <li><strong>Test hashtag and keyword strategies.</strong> On Instagram, niche hashtags (10,000-500,000 posts) drive more incremental reach than mega-hashtags. On LinkedIn, topic tags and early comments from connections outside your follower base expand distribution.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — confusing reach with impressions in reports</div>
          <p>Many social media reports hand stakeholders impression numbers labelled as "people reached." This inflates perceived performance by 2-5x. Always verify which metric the platform is actually reporting in the column header before sharing numbers upward.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common reach mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Chasing follower count instead of reach rate.</strong> A 100,000-follower account with 2% reach delivers fewer eyeballs than a 10,000-follower account with 30% reach. Reach rate matters more than raw follower count.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring format experimentation.</strong> Defaulting to static images because "they're easier" cedes algorithmic distribution to creators using Reels and carousels.</li>
          <li><strong>Measuring reach in isolation.</strong> High reach with 0.1% engagement rate means your content is visible but irrelevant. Pair reach with engagement rate and link clicks to get the full picture.</li>
          <li><strong>Benchmarking against wrong accounts.</strong> An account in a niche topic will always have higher reach rates than a broad-topic account because algorithms favour specific content for precise audiences.</li>
          <li><strong>Not separating organic and paid reach.</strong> Running ads while tracking "total reach" creates the illusion of organic growth and masks the real organic reach trend.</li>
        </ul>

